#Requires -Version 7.0
<#
.SYNOPSIS
    Programmatically updates all on-premises data gateway clusters across
    a tenant using Update-DataGatewayClusterMember, with Azure Key Vault
    integration and baseline version validation.

.DESCRIPTION
    This script:
      1. Retrieves service principal credentials from Azure Key Vault.
      2. Authenticates to the Data Gateway service via the service principal.
      3. Discovers all gateway clusters in the tenant (Organization scope).
      4. VALIDATES that every gateway meets the November 2025 baseline
         version (3000.294). Halts execution if any gateway is too old.
      5. For multi-member clusters, performs a rolling update: disable,
         drain, update, re-enable, next member.
      6. For single-member clusters, updates directly.
      7. Polls -CheckStatus after each update to confirm completion.
      8. Outputs a summary report of all actions taken.

.NOTES
    ======================================================================
    AZURE KEY VAULT SETUP (one-time, manual steps in the Azure Portal)
    ======================================================================

    Before running this script, you must create an Azure Key Vault and
    store three secrets in it. Follow these steps:

    STEP 1 — Create the Key Vault
      1. Sign in to the Azure Portal (portal.azure.com).
      2. Search for "Key vaults" in the top search bar and select it.
      3. Click "+ Create".
      4. Choose your Subscription and Resource Group (or create one).
      5. Enter a globally unique Key Vault name
         (e.g., "kv-gateway-automation").
      6. Select a Region close to your gateway infrastructure.
      7. Leave the pricing tier as "Standard".
      8. Click "Review + create", then "Create".

    STEP 2 — Store Your Secrets
      1. Open your new Key Vault in the portal.
      2. In the left menu, go to "Objects" > "Secrets".
      3. Click "+ Generate/Import" and create three secrets:

         Secret Name              | Value
         -------------------------|--------------------------------------
         GatewaySpAppId           | Your App Registration's Application
                                  | (Client) ID  (a GUID)
         GatewaySpSecret          | Your App Registration's Client Secret
                                  | value (the string you copied at
                                  | creation time)
         GatewaySpTenantId        | Your Entra ID Tenant (Directory) ID
                                  | (a GUID)

      4. For each secret, click "Create" after entering the name and value.

    STEP 3 — Grant the Service Principal Access to Read Secrets
      The same service principal that will run this script needs
      permission to read its own credentials from Key Vault.

      Option A — Azure RBAC (recommended):
        1. In the Key Vault, go to "Access control (IAM)".
        2. Click "+ Add" > "Add role assignment".
        3. Select the role "Key Vault Secrets User".
        4. Under "Members", search for your App Registration name
           and select it.
        5. Click "Review + assign".

      Option B — Vault Access Policy (legacy):
        1. In the Key Vault, go to "Access policies".
        2. Click "+ Add Access Policy".
        3. Under "Secret permissions", check "Get" and "List".
        4. Under "Select principal", find your App Registration.
        5. Click "Add", then "Save".

    STEP 4 — (If running from Azure Automation / Fabric)
      If you use a Managed Identity instead of a service principal,
      grant the Managed Identity the same "Key Vault Secrets User"
      role from Step 3, and use Connect-AzAccount -Identity in the
      script instead of the explicit credential login shown below.

    ======================================================================
    RUNNING THIS SCRIPT INSIDE MICROSOFT FABRIC
    ======================================================================

    Fabric notebooks run on Apache Spark (PySpark/Scala/R) and do NOT
    natively support PowerShell 7 modules like DataGateway. You have
    three viable options for executing this from within the Fabric
    ecosystem:

    OPTION A — Fabric Data Pipeline + Azure Automation Runbook
      (Recommended for production)

      This is the cleanest and most scalable approach. The idea is to
      host this PowerShell script as an Azure Automation Runbook and
      trigger it from a Fabric Data Factory Pipeline using a Web
      Activity or Webhook Activity.

      1. Create an Azure Automation Account in the Azure Portal.
      2. Under "Runbooks", click "+ Create a runbook".
         - Name: "Update-TenantGateways"
         - Runbook type: "PowerShell"
         - Runtime version: 7.2
      3. Paste this script into the runbook editor.
      4. Under "Modules" in your Automation Account, import:
         - Az.Accounts
         - Az.KeyVault
         - DataGateway (upload the .nupkg from PowerShell Gallery)
      5. Publish the runbook.
      6. Create a Webhook on the runbook (Runbook > Webhooks > Add).
         Copy the webhook URL (shown only once).
      7. In Fabric Data Factory, create a Pipeline and add a
         "Web Activity":
         - URL: your webhook URL
         - Method: POST
         - Body: {} (empty JSON)
      8. Schedule the pipeline to run monthly, or trigger it manually.

      The runbook executes in Azure with full PowerShell 7 support,
      the DataGateway module, and access to Key Vault via Managed
      Identity or service principal. The Fabric pipeline simply
      orchestrates when it runs.

    OPTION B — Fabric Notebook (PySpark) Calling REST APIs Directly
      (Alternative if you want everything inside Fabric)

      Instead of using the DataGateway PowerShell module, rewrite the
      gateway management logic as direct REST API calls from a Python
      notebook. This avoids the PowerShell dependency entirely:

        import requests, msal

        # Get token via MSAL
        app = msal.ConfidentialClientApplication(
            client_id=app_id,
            client_credential=client_secret,
            authority=f"https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant_id}"
        )
        token = app.acquire_token_for_client(
            scopes=["https://analysis.windows.net/powerbi/api/.default"]
        )

        # Call gateway APIs
        headers = {"Authorization": f"Bearer {token['access_token']}"}
        gateways = requests.get(
            "https://api.powerbi.com/v1.0/myorg/gateways",
            headers=headers
        ).json()

      However, the Update-DataGatewayClusterMember functionality
      may not yet have a REST API equivalent (it is a PowerShell-only
      preview feature). In that case, Option A remains the best path.

    OPTION C — Fabric Notebook Shelling Out to PowerShell
      (Quick and dirty — not recommended for production)

      Fabric Spark nodes have a Linux OS. You can shell out to
      pwsh (PowerShell Core) if it is available in the runtime:

        import subprocess
        result = subprocess.run(
            ["pwsh", "-File", "/path/to/script.ps1"],
            capture_output=True, text=True
        )

      This is fragile because the Fabric Spark runtime does not
      guarantee pwsh availability or the ability to install the
      DataGateway module. Use Option A instead.

    ======================================================================

.PARAMETER KeyVaultName
    The name of the Azure Key Vault containing the service principal
    credentials (e.g., "kv-gateway-automation").

.PARAMETER AppIdSecretName
    The name of the Key Vault secret holding the Application (Client) ID.
    Default: "GatewaySpAppId"

.PARAMETER ClientSecretName
    The name of the Key Vault secret holding the Client Secret value.
    Default: "GatewaySpSecret"

.PARAMETER TenantIdSecretName
    The name of the Key Vault secret holding the Tenant (Directory) ID.
    Default: "GatewaySpTenantId"

.PARAMETER DrainWaitMinutes
    Minutes to wait for in-flight queries to drain after disabling a
    gateway member. Default is 30.

.PARAMETER PollIntervalSeconds
    Seconds between status polls when checking update progress.
    Default is 60.

.PARAMETER MaxPollAttempts
    Maximum number of polling attempts before timing out.
    Default is 30 (i.e., 30 minutes at 60-second intervals).

.PARAMETER WhatIf
    If specified, the script discovers, validates, and reports on all
    gateways but does NOT trigger any updates. Use this for a dry run.

.EXAMPLE
    .\Update-AllTenantGateways.ps1 -KeyVaultName "kv-gateway-automation"

.EXAMPLE
    # Dry run — discover, validate versions, report only
    .\Update-AllTenantGateways.ps1 -KeyVaultName "kv-gateway-automation" -WhatIf

.EXAMPLE
    # Custom drain time for long-running refresh environments
    .\Update-AllTenantGateways.ps1 `
        -KeyVaultName "kv-gateway-automation" `
        -DrainWaitMinutes 60 `
        -PollIntervalSeconds 90
#>

[CmdletBinding(SupportsShouldProcess)]
param(
    [Parameter(Mandatory)]
    [string]$KeyVaultName,

    [string]$AppIdSecretName     = "GatewaySpAppId",
    [string]$ClientSecretName    = "GatewaySpSecret",
    [string]$TenantIdSecretName  = "GatewaySpTenantId",

    [int]$DrainWaitMinutes       = 30,
    [int]$PollIntervalSeconds    = 60,
    [int]$MaxPollAttempts        = 30
)

# ============================================================
# CONSTANTS
# ============================================================

# The November 2025 release is the baseline version required
# for Update-DataGatewayClusterMember to function.
# Version 3000.294 = November 2025 release.
$BASELINE_VERSION = [version]"3000.294.0"
$BASELINE_LABEL   = "November 2025 (3000.294)"

# ============================================================
# SECTION 1: Module Check and Installation
# ============================================================

$requiredModules = @("Az.Accounts", "Az.KeyVault", "DataGateway")

foreach ($mod in $requiredModules) {
    if (-not (Get-Module -ListAvailable -Name $mod)) {
        Write-Host "[SETUP] Module '$mod' not found. Installing..." -ForegroundColor Yellow
        Install-Module -Name $mod -Scope CurrentUser -Force -AllowClobber
    }
}
Import-Module Az.Accounts -Force
Import-Module Az.KeyVault -Force
Import-Module DataGateway  -Force

Write-Host "[SETUP] All required modules loaded." -ForegroundColor Green

# ============================================================
# SECTION 2: Retrieve Credentials from Azure Key Vault
# ============================================================

Write-Host "`n[KEYVAULT] Authenticating to Azure..." -ForegroundColor Cyan

# If running in Azure Automation with a Managed Identity, use:
#   Connect-AzAccount -Identity
# If running locally or in CI/CD with existing Az context, the
# existing session may already be authenticated.
try {
    $azContext = Get-AzContext
    if (-not $azContext) {
        # Interactive login fallback — for local dev/testing.
        # In Azure Automation, replace with: Connect-AzAccount -Identity
        Connect-AzAccount
    }
    Write-Host "[KEYVAULT] Azure session active as: $($azContext.Account.Id ?? 'Managed Identity')" -ForegroundColor Green
}
catch {
    Write-Error "[KEYVAULT] Failed to authenticate to Azure: $_"
    exit 1
}

Write-Host "[KEYVAULT] Retrieving secrets from vault '$KeyVaultName'..." -ForegroundColor Cyan

try {
    $ApplicationId = Get-AzKeyVaultSecret `
        -VaultName $KeyVaultName `
        -Name $AppIdSecretName `
        -AsPlainText

    $ClientSecret = Get-AzKeyVaultSecret `
        -VaultName $KeyVaultName `
        -Name $ClientSecretName `
        -AsPlainText

    $TenantId = Get-AzKeyVaultSecret `
        -VaultName $KeyVaultName `
        -Name $TenantIdSecretName `
        -AsPlainText

    # Validate that none came back empty
    if ([string]::IsNullOrWhiteSpace($ApplicationId) -or
        [string]::IsNullOrWhiteSpace($ClientSecret) -or
        [string]::IsNullOrWhiteSpace($TenantId)) {
        throw "One or more Key Vault secrets returned empty values."
    }

    Write-Host "[KEYVAULT] All three secrets retrieved successfully." -ForegroundColor Green
}
catch {
    Write-Error "[KEYVAULT] Failed to retrieve secrets: $_"
    Write-Error "Ensure the Key Vault '$KeyVaultName' exists, the secret names are correct, and the running identity has 'Key Vault Secrets User' permissions."
    exit 1
}

# ============================================================
# SECTION 3: Authenticate to Data Gateway Service
# ============================================================

Write-Host "`n[AUTH] Connecting to Data Gateway service..." -ForegroundColor Cyan

$secureSecret = $ClientSecret | ConvertTo-SecureString -AsPlainText -Force

try {
    Connect-DataGatewayServiceAccount `
        -ApplicationId $ApplicationId `
        -ClientSecret $secureSecret `
        -Tenant $TenantId
    Write-Host "[AUTH] Successfully authenticated to Data Gateway service." -ForegroundColor Green
}
catch {
    Write-Error "[AUTH] Failed to authenticate: $_"
    exit 1
}

# Clear the plain-text secret from memory as a security precaution
$ClientSecret = $null
[System.GC]::Collect()

# ============================================================
# SECTION 4: Discover All Gateway Clusters (Tenant-Wide)
# ============================================================

Write-Host "`n[DISCOVERY] Retrieving all gateway clusters in the tenant..." -ForegroundColor Cyan

try {
    $allClusters = Get-DataGatewayCluster -Scope Organization
}
catch {
    Write-Error "[DISCOVERY] Failed to retrieve clusters: $_"
    exit 1
}

if (-not $allClusters -or $allClusters.Count -eq 0) {
    Write-Host "[DISCOVERY] No gateway clusters found in this tenant." -ForegroundColor Yellow
    exit 0
}

Write-Host "[DISCOVERY] Found $($allClusters.Count) gateway cluster(s).`n" -ForegroundColor Green

# ============================================================
# SECTION 5: Build Inventory and Validate Baseline Version
# ============================================================

$inventory       = @()
$belowBaseline   = @()

foreach ($cluster in $allClusters) {
    $clusterId   = $cluster.Id
    $clusterName = $cluster.Name

    try {
        $status = Get-DataGatewayClusterStatus `
            -GatewayClusterId $clusterId `
            -Scope Organization

        $versionStr = $status.GatewayVersion
        $parsedVersion = $null

        # Parse the version string. Gateway versions look like
        # "3000.294.5" or "3000.298.0". We need at least 3000.294.x
        if ($versionStr -and $versionStr -match '^\d+\.\d+') {
            try { $parsedVersion = [version]$versionStr } catch { }
        }

        $meetsBaseline = $false
        if ($parsedVersion) {
            # Compare Major.Minor (e.g., 3000.294 >= 3000.294)
            $meetsBaseline = ($parsedVersion -ge $BASELINE_VERSION)
        }

        $entry = [PSCustomObject]@{
            ClusterName    = $clusterName
            ClusterId      = $clusterId
            ClusterStatus  = $status.ClusterStatus
            GatewayVersion = $versionStr ?? "Unknown"
            MeetsBaseline  = $meetsBaseline
            UpgradeState   = $status.GatewayUpgradeState
            MemberCount    = if ($cluster.MemberGateways) {
                                 $cluster.MemberGateways.Count
                             } else { 1 }
        }

        $inventory += $entry

        if (-not $meetsBaseline) {
            $belowBaseline += $entry
        }
    }
    catch {
        Write-Warning "[INVENTORY] Could not get status for '$clusterName' ($clusterId): $_"
        $entry = [PSCustomObject]@{
            ClusterName    = $clusterName
            ClusterId      = $clusterId
            ClusterStatus  = "Unknown"
            GatewayVersion = "Unknown"
            MeetsBaseline  = $false
            UpgradeState   = "Unknown"
            MemberCount    = 0
        }
        $inventory    += $entry
        $belowBaseline += $entry
    }
}

# Display the inventory
Write-Host "==================== GATEWAY INVENTORY ====================" -ForegroundColor Cyan
$inventory | Format-Table ClusterName, GatewayVersion, MeetsBaseline, ClusterStatus, MemberCount -AutoSize
Write-Host "==========================================================`n" -ForegroundColor Cyan

# ============================================================
# SECTION 6: Baseline Version Gate — Halt If Any Below Minimum
# ============================================================

if ($belowBaseline.Count -gt 0) {
    Write-Host "!!! BASELINE VERSION CHECK FAILED !!!" -ForegroundColor Red
    Write-Host ""
    Write-Host "The following gateway cluster(s) are running a version BELOW" -ForegroundColor Red
    Write-Host "the required $BASELINE_LABEL baseline:" -ForegroundColor Red
    Write-Host ""

    $belowBaseline | Format-Table ClusterName, GatewayVersion, ClusterId -AutoSize

    Write-Host "Update-DataGatewayClusterMember requires all gateways to" -ForegroundColor Red
    Write-Host "be at version $BASELINE_VERSION or later." -ForegroundColor Red
    Write-Host ""
    Write-Host "REMEDIATION:" -ForegroundColor Yellow
    Write-Host "  For each gateway below baseline, log into the gateway" -ForegroundColor Yellow
    Write-Host "  machine and run:" -ForegroundColor Yellow
    Write-Host "    Install-DataGateway -AcceptConditions" -ForegroundColor White
    Write-Host "  This will upgrade the gateway to the latest version." -ForegroundColor Yellow
    Write-Host "  Alternatively, download the latest installer from:" -ForegroundColor Yellow
    Write-Host "    https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=2116849" -ForegroundColor White
    Write-Host ""

    # Throw a terminating error so that any calling orchestrator
    # (Azure Automation, Fabric Pipeline, etc.) sees a failure.
    throw "HALTED: $($belowBaseline.Count) gateway(s) below baseline version $BASELINE_VERSION. See output above for details."
}

Write-Host "[VALIDATE] All gateways meet the $BASELINE_LABEL baseline. Proceeding.`n" -ForegroundColor Green

# ============================================================
# SECTION 7: If -WhatIf, stop here after validation
# ============================================================

if ($WhatIfPreference) {
    Write-Host "[DRY RUN] -WhatIf specified. No updates will be performed." -ForegroundColor Yellow
    Write-Host "[DRY RUN] All gateways passed the baseline check."
    Write-Host "[DRY RUN] Remove -WhatIf to execute updates."
    exit 0
}

# ============================================================
# SECTION 8: Helper Functions
# ============================================================

function Wait-ForUpdateCompletion {
    param(
        [Parameter(Mandatory)][string]$ClusterId,
        [string]$MemberId,
        [int]$IntervalSec = 60,
        [int]$MaxAttempts = 30
    )

    for ($i = 1; $i -le $MaxAttempts; $i++) {
        Write-Host "    [POLL $i/$MaxAttempts] Checking update status..." -ForegroundColor DarkGray

        try {
            $checkParams = @{
                GatewayClusterId = $ClusterId
                CheckStatus      = $true
            }
            if ($MemberId) {
                $checkParams["MemberGatewayId"] = $MemberId
            }

            $result = Update-DataGatewayClusterMember @checkParams
            $state  = $result.Status

            Write-Host "    [POLL] Current state: $state" -ForegroundColor DarkGray

            if ($state -eq "Completed" -or $state -eq "Succeeded") {
                return @{ Success = $true; State = $state }
            }
            elseif ($state -eq "Failed") {
                return @{ Success = $false; State = $state }
            }
        }
        catch {
            Write-Warning "    [POLL] Error checking status: $_"
        }

        Start-Sleep -Seconds $IntervalSec
    }

    return @{ Success = $false; State = "Timeout" }
}

function Update-SingleMember {
    param(
        [Parameter(Mandatory)][string]$ClusterId,
        [string]$MemberId,
        [string]$DisplayName
    )

    Write-Host "  [UPDATE] Triggering update for '$DisplayName'..." -ForegroundColor Yellow

    try {
        $updateParams = @{ GatewayClusterId = $ClusterId }
        if ($MemberId) {
            $updateParams["MemberGatewayId"] = $MemberId
        }

        Update-DataGatewayClusterMember @updateParams
        Write-Host "  [UPDATE] Update command sent. Polling for completion..." -ForegroundColor Yellow
    }
    catch {
        Write-Error "  [UPDATE] Failed to trigger update for '$DisplayName': $_"
        return $false
    }

    $result = Wait-ForUpdateCompletion `
        -ClusterId $ClusterId `
        -MemberId $MemberId `
        -IntervalSec $PollIntervalSeconds `
        -MaxAttempts $MaxPollAttempts

    if ($result.Success) {
        Write-Host "  [UPDATE] '$DisplayName' updated successfully." -ForegroundColor Green
        return $true
    }
    else {
        Write-Warning "  [UPDATE] '$DisplayName' update ended with state: $($result.State)"
        return $false
    }
}

# ============================================================
# SECTION 9: Execute Rolling Updates
# ============================================================

$report = @()

foreach ($cluster in $allClusters) {
    $clusterId   = $cluster.Id
    $clusterName = $cluster.Name
    $members     = $cluster.MemberGateways

    Write-Host "============================================" -ForegroundColor Cyan
    Write-Host "Processing cluster: $clusterName ($clusterId)" -ForegroundColor Cyan
    Write-Host "============================================" -ForegroundColor Cyan

    # ----------------------------------------------------------
    # Case A: Single-member cluster
    # ----------------------------------------------------------
    if (-not $members -or $members.Count -le 1) {
        Write-Host "  Single-member cluster — updating directly." -ForegroundColor White

        $success = Update-SingleMember `
            -ClusterId $clusterId `
            -DisplayName $clusterName

        $report += [PSCustomObject]@{
            Cluster  = $clusterName
            Member   = "(single)"
            Action   = "Update"
            Result   = if ($success) { "Success" } else { "Failed" }
        }
    }
    # ----------------------------------------------------------
    # Case B: Multi-member cluster — rolling update
    # ----------------------------------------------------------
    else {
        Write-Host "  Multi-member cluster ($($members.Count) members) — rolling update." -ForegroundColor White

        foreach ($member in $members) {
            $memberId   = $member.Id
            $memberName = $member.Name

            Write-Host "`n  --- Member: $memberName ($memberId) ---" -ForegroundColor White

            # Step 1: Disable the member
            Write-Host "  [STEP 1] Disabling member '$memberName'..." -ForegroundColor Yellow
            try {
                Set-DataGatewayCluster `
                    -GatewayClusterId $clusterId `
                    -MemberGatewayId $memberId `
                    -Enabled $false
                Write-Host "  [STEP 1] Member disabled." -ForegroundColor Green
            }
            catch {
                Write-Warning "  [STEP 1] Could not disable member: $_. Proceeding anyway."
            }

            # Step 2: Wait for in-flight queries to drain
            Write-Host "  [STEP 2] Waiting $DrainWaitMinutes min for queries to drain..." -ForegroundColor Yellow
            Start-Sleep -Seconds ($DrainWaitMinutes * 60)

            # Step 3: Trigger the update
            $success = Update-SingleMember `
                -ClusterId $clusterId `
                -MemberId $memberId `
                -DisplayName "$clusterName/$memberName"

            # Step 4: Re-enable the member
            Write-Host "  [STEP 4] Re-enabling member '$memberName'..." -ForegroundColor Yellow
            try {
                Set-DataGatewayCluster `
                    -GatewayClusterId $clusterId `
                    -MemberGatewayId $memberId `
                    -Enabled $true
                Write-Host "  [STEP 4] Member re-enabled." -ForegroundColor Green
            }
            catch {
                Write-Warning "  [STEP 4] Could not re-enable member: $_. Manual intervention needed."
            }

            $report += [PSCustomObject]@{
                Cluster  = $clusterName
                Member   = $memberName
                Action   = "Rolling Update"
                Result   = if ($success) { "Success" } else { "Failed" }
            }

            Write-Host "  --- Member '$memberName' complete. ---`n" -ForegroundColor White
        }
    }
}

# ============================================================
# SECTION 10: Summary Report
# ============================================================

Write-Host "`n===================== UPDATE REPORT =====================" -ForegroundColor Cyan
$report | Format-Table -AutoSize
Write-Host "========================================================`n" -ForegroundColor Cyan

$failed = $report | Where-Object { $_.Result -eq "Failed" }
if ($failed) {
    Write-Warning "The following members failed to update:"
    $failed | Format-Table -AutoSize
    Write-Host "Review the output above and check gateway logs on the affected machines."
    exit 1
}
else {
    Write-Host "All gateways updated successfully." -ForegroundColor Green
    exit 0
}
